Throwback Thursday: In a 40 second segment, I manage to irk both political parties. 

On a personal note, I’ve consistently stood for the national anthem, while also showing respect for those who peacefully knelt. Interestingly, the controversy around the kneel stemmed from its purpose rather than the act itself causing much of its message to be lost. 

It’s worth noting that a Navy SEAL recommended the kneeling. Additionally, prior to 2009, virtually no NFL team or player stood  during the anthem. 

Anyway, I want you all to witness how swiftly the producers urged her to shift the topic after I spoke. The amusing part? They gave me the wrong earpiece, so I overheard everything they said. 😂

Question: If you at all believe there is any logic to my statements, consider why every instance I had something rational to share, all media platforms abruptly interrupted me? They changed the subject. I assure you, this happened and still happens to me. 

At the time I began to believe perhaps media didn’t want cohesiveness amongst its citizens which is why they pushed brush fire narratives. Or perhaps media outlets are simply a conduit to provide “entertainment” labeled as news (at times). 

Then I realized that mainstream media is run by humans  themselves. It’s actually NOT a machine. So what am I missing?
Flesh vs. Spirit. The spirit is AWARE that the air we breathe has a limited lifespan. The flesh begs autopilot. Only memories and stories will be shared when we go. Write yours on peoples hearts. 🙏🏾

Has anyone else observed the trend where corporate entities specifically highlight achievements by individuals of the black community as a gesture of promoting diversity and unity? While possibly well-intentioned, this approach inadvertently emphasizes the segregation linked to acknowledging one’s skin color in relation to their accomplishments.

By showcasing a “black author,” “black lawyer,” “black referees” or any professional followed by the qualifier “black,” there’s a risk of indirectly reinforcing a sense of separate success among children of color. While acknowledging these achievements is important, it’s crucial to consider the broader implications.

While these acknowledgments occur, by the number, the urgent needs within inner-city communities persist. It’s uncertain how precisely sharing a photograph contributes to addressing the tangible needs of these communities.

When individuals suggest that troubled communities need the church, some respond by stating that Jesus himself doesn’t directly supply food and clothing. However, when corporate America decides social media needs a gesture, like this photo, well, I guess that is sufficient. - @nfl photo 📸
